Results
=======

Notes
-----

miniply seems to be the fastest parser in nearly all cases, but this might be
skewed by it being better suited for the particular mesh structure I'm trying
to populate.

Happly makes very heavy use of STL containers as a way of presenting the data,
which leads to a lot of copying and data conversion to get it into my mesh
structure.

RPly's callback structure means it has very low memory overhead but it has
the most complicated API by far. It returns all numeric values as double -
including vertex indices - which leads to a lot of typecasting.

I haven't been able to figure out how to extract face data using tinyply yet.
It's being loaded, but I don't know what to do with the binary blob I get from
it. As such the results for tinyply below don't include time to load or
triangulate faces.

I prewarm the disk cache for each file before running the parsers. I do this
by streaming the entire file into memory via a 1 MB buffer, then discarding
the buffer.


Test hardware used
------------------

The laptop used for the results below was:

- Windows 10, v1903
- Intel Core i7-6700HQ CPU, 2.6 GHz
- 16 GB Dual-channel DDR4 RAM
- Samsung MZVPV512 SSD, theoretical peak read speed of 1165 MB/s

All times reported below are in milliseconds.
